alse, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9686149954795837, "span": {"begin": 1086, "end": 1094}}, {"id": ["mesh:C074283"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estradiol benzoate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996368885040283, "span": {"begin": 1101, "end": 1119}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "17beta-estradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996099472045898, "span": {"begin": 1121, "end": 1137}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999464213848114, "span": {"begin": 1186, "end": 1194}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3814"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "kisspeptin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9865356087684631, "span": {"begin": 1228, "end": 1238}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "anteroventral periventricular nucleus (AVPV) neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7626109719276428, "span": {"begin": 1244, "end": 1296}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990019202232361, "span": {"begin": 1393, "end": 1401}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen receptor alpha", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9923715591430664, "span": {"begin": 1393, "end": 1416}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mammalian cell lines", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.5267593860626221, "span": {"begin": 1461, "end": 1481}}, {"id": ["mesh:C510606"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "EPA 2025", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9451597929000854, "span": {"begin": 1497, "end": 1505}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ERa", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9775941371917725, "span": {"begin": 1612, "end": 1615}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3814"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "kisspeptin genes", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.994746208190918, "span": {"begin": 1620, "end": 1636}}], "text": "Previous studies have shown that estrogen exposures to organisms have caused increases in gonadotropin levels despite gonadotropin-releasing hormone neurons not expressing estrogen receptors. Recent studies have shown kisspeptin neurons located within the hypothalamus to express estrogen, androgen, and progesterone receptors(Clarkson et al., 2008). Fluorescence-activated cell sorting in mice found 99% and 70% of KISS1 neurons in the arcuate and anteroventral periventricular regions of the hypothalamus express ER&alpha; receptors (Smith et al., 2005). Estrogen exposures thereby should elicit an increase in kisspeptin expression.  Increased activation of estrogen receptor alpha and resulting increased release of kisspeptin from anteroventral periventricular nucleus (AVPV) neurons have been studied in laboratory mammals by addition of estrogenic compounds (Adachi et al. 2007; Clarkson et al. 2008; Tomikawa et al. 2012) and toxicants (Wang et al. 2014) known to increase estrogen receptor activation. &nbsp;Studies involving dosing of laboratory mammals with various forms of estrogen (e.g. estradiol benzoate, 17beta-estradiol) are supportive of the mechanism of exposure to estrogen compounds causing an increase in kisspeptin from anteroventral periventricular nucleus (AVPV) neurons (Adachi et al. 2007; Clarkson et al. 2008; Tomikawa et al. 2012). &nbsp;Increased activation of estrogen receptor alpha, or estrogenicity, has also been studied in mammalian cell lines in vitro (U.S. EPA 2025). &nbsp;Gene knock-out and ovariectomized animal studies have been useful in establishing essentiality of ERa and kisspeptin genes in the hypothalamus- pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis, with hormone addition restoring function (Adachi et al. 2007; Clarkson et al. 2008; Tomikawa et al. 2012). &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:45:51 +0000 2026"}